  <static seed="999" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/GraphingQuadratics/IdentifyAxisVertex100.pg">
    <statement><p>Find the axis of symmetry and vertex of the quadratic function.</p>
<p><m>{y}={x^{2}+3x-3}</m></p>
<p>Axis of symmetry: <fillin characters="13" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
<p>Vertex: <fillin characters="13" name="AnSwEr0002"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>x = -{\frac{3}{2}}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\left(-{\frac{3}{2}},-{\frac{21}{4}}\right)</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>This quadratic function is given in standard form. Identify that:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ a=1,b=3,c=-3 }</m></p>
<p>To find the parabola<rsq/>s axis of symmetry, we use the formula <m>\displaystyle{x=-\frac{b}{2a}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
  x \amp = -\frac{b}{2a} \\
   \amp = -\frac{3}{2(1)} \\
   \amp = {-{\frac{3}{2}}}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>This parabola<rsq/>s axis of symmetry is the line <m>\displaystyle{x={-{\frac{3}{2}}}}</m>.</p>
<p>Next, substitute <m>\displaystyle{x={-{\frac{3}{2}}}}</m> into <m>\displaystyle{{y}={x^{2}+3x-3}}</m>, and we have:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   y \amp = 1\left({-{\frac{3}{2}}}\right)^{2}+3\left({-{\frac{3}{2}}}\right) - 3 \\
    \amp = 1 \cdot {{\frac{9}{4}}} -{\frac{9}{2}}  - 3 \\
    \amp = {-{\frac{21}{4}}}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>This parabola<rsq/>s vertex is at <m>\displaystyle{\left({-{\frac{3}{2}}},{-{\frac{21}{4}}}\right)}</m>.</p>
</solution>
